  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Why does Wazuh need Postfix to send email alerts?</h3>
  <p>Wazuh's internal mail client only relays to a local SMTP server. Postfix acts as that local relay (<code>smtp_server localhost</code>) and forwards the message to Gmail or Microsoft 365 over port 587 with TLS, handling the SASL authentication that Wazuh itself cannot perform.</p>

  <h3>Do I need an app password for Gmail SMTP?</h3>
  <p>Yes. Gmail blocks your normal account password for SMTP. You must enable two-step verification and then generate a 16-character app password at <a href="https://myaccount.google.com/apppasswords" target="_blank" rel="noopener">myaccount.google.com/apppasswords</a>, which you store in <code>/etc/postfix/sasl_passwd</code>.</p>

  <h3>Which SMTP server and port should I use for Gmail and Microsoft 365?</h3>
  <p>Both providers use port 587 with STARTTLS. Gmail uses <code>smtp.gmail.com:587</code> and Microsoft 365 uses <code>smtp.office365.com:587</code>. You set this value as the <code>relayhost</code> in <code>/etc/postfix/main.cf</code>.</p>

  <h3>From which alert level does Wazuh send emails by default?</h3>
  <p>By default Wazuh sends email for alerts of level 7 and above. You can override this per rule with an <code>&lt;email_alerts&gt;</code> block that targets a specific <code>rule_id</code>, so even a lower-level rule can notify a dedicated recipient.</p>

  <h3>Which ISO 27001 and ENS controls do email alerts cover?</h3>
  <p>Email alerts support ISO 27001:2022 controls A.5.24, A.5.25, A.5.26, A.8.15 and A.8.16, and ENS (RD 311/2022) measures op.mon.1, op.mon.3, op.exp.7 and op.exp.9, all related to incident detection, notification and logging.</p>

